    "---\n",
    "### 4.3 Accuracy vs K-hop Degree\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why this matters:**\n",
    "1-hop degree measures direct connectivity, but a GNN's actual receptive field is its k-hop neighbourhood. Two nodes can share the same 1-hop degree while sitting in very different structural contexts: one in a densely connected region (large 2-hop neighbourhood), one in a sparse region (small 2-hop neighbourhood).\n",
    "\n",
    "The k-hop degree of a node is the number of distinct nodes reachable within `k` hops — the size of the receptive field for a k-layer GNN. Studying accuracy vs k-hop degree separates **structural richness** (how much information is potentially available) from **raw local connectivity**.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is especially relevant for GNNs with `num_layers = 2` (k=1 message-passing hops in this config): a node with 1-hop degree 3 but 2-hop degree 300 receives aggregated information from 300 upstream nodes, not just 3. The accuracy pattern over k-hop degree can reveal whether it is the *immediate* neighbourhood or the *extended* neighbourhood that drives performance.\n"
   ]
